Designed and implemented an AI-driven conversational chatbot (defect triaging) to triage the defects created in non-prod environments by integrating with available tools (logs, code commits, etc..,) and knowledge bases (history defects, SME inputs, etc.,). As the adoption increases, the defect triaging system slowed down significantly. Even though we added more server power, it wasn't helping. We were paying for high-end AI processing, but tickets were taking minutes instead of seconds to resolve.

Where I started
I first looked at our Servers logs and logging DB. I thought the system was crashing because too many people were using it at once. I increased the memory and CPU power, but the speed didn't improve at all.

What I checked next
I started tracking the AIâ€™s behavior for each ticket. I found that when a bug report included a very long application log (like a 20-page document), the AI became "overwhelmed." It was trying to read every single line of data before making a decision.

What evidence changed my direction
I realized the issue wasn't our servers; it was "Data Noise." We were sending too much useless information to the AI. This caused two problems:
High Costs: We were paying for "tokens" (words) that weren't needed.
Latency: The more data we sent, the slower the AI got, creating a massive "traffic jam" in our pipeline.
Also, the audit log showed that the application log extraction process took considerable amount of time.

How I verified the fix
I changed the workflow to a Three-Step Process:
Step 1: A smaller, cheaper AI "cleaned" the data first (after consulting with SME), removing the junk and keeping only the errors.
Step 2: Python concurrency and dedicated server for hosting the log extraction API with enough replicas
Step 3: The main AI analyzed only that clean summary.

The Result: 
The system became 3x faster and our AI costs dropped by 60%. I confirmed the fix by running 200 complex bugs through the system, proving it was now both faster and just as accurate as a human.

