--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

The Situation:
As a young project lead, i was managing the EU invoicing product in Ford Motor Company. As this is related to Invoicing, any changes in the EU business process will have impact on my invoicing product and the team was loaded with huge number of projects/enhancements. During a busy project with a tight deadline, I tried to "lead by example" by taking on all the hardest tasks myself. I thought I was protecting my team from stress and making sure the work was perfect.

The Feedback:
A teammate told me that by doing all the difficult work, I had become a bottleneck. Because I was overwhelmed, the rest of the team was stuck waiting for me to finish. They also felt like I didn't trust them with important work, which lowered their morale.

What I Asked:
I was surprised, so I asked:
"Do you feel ready to take on these harder tasks if I support you?"
"Is the team more upset about the amount of work or the lack of trust?"

What I Changed:
I realized that my action was actually hurting the team. I changed my approach:
Delegated More: I handed over tasks to others, even if I could do them slightly faster, so I was free to help the whole group.
Mentored Instead of Doing: I assigned the hard tasks to team members and acted as their advisor instead of doing the work for them.
Shared Visibility: We used a "Task Board" so everyone could see who was doing what. If I took on too much, the team was allowed to tell me to share the load.

The Result:
The project finished faster because work wasn't stuck on my desk. The team felt more confident because they learned how to handle difficult tasks. I learned that my real job is to empower the team, not just do the work and i started focusing on the financials and new project requirements.
